To solve this, we need to determine the number of ways to assign 4 different officers (president, secretary, treasurer, and morale officer) to 10 club members, where each member can only hold one office. This is a permutation problem where we are selecting 4 members out of 10 without replacement and considering the order of selection.

The number of ways to choose the officers is given by the permutation formula \(P(n, k) = \frac{n!}{(n-k)!}\), where \(n\) is the total number of members (10), and \(k\) is the number of positions (4). Therefore, the number of ways to choose the officers is \(P(10, 4) = \frac{10!}{(10-4)!} = \frac{10!}{6!} = 10 \times 9 \times 8 \times 7\).

